    • Method Detail

      • getDimension

        int getDimension()
        A dimension of a vector is determined based on the number of elements it holds. Such as, a two-dimensional vector could be represented as, (v1, v12); the same as an n-dimensional vector can be represented as (v1, v2,...., vn), where n belongs to the set of natural numbers "N".

        Many vector operations are dimension dependant, such as addition, subtraction, and multiplication. Which requires two vectors must be in the same dimension.

        Returns:
        the dimension of the vector

      • getMagnitude

        double getMagnitude()
        The magnitude of a vector, also known as "norm", is square root of the sum all the vector elements powered by 2. A magnitude of a vector is represented by the length of a vector and written as |V| for vector V.

        For n-dimensional vector, the magnitude is defined as; |v| = sqrt(v1^2 + v2^2 + ... + vn^2).

        Returns:
        the magnitude of the vector

      • getMagnitude

        double getMagnitude​(Rounding.POINT decimals)
        The magnitude of a vector, also known as "norm", is square root of the sum all the vector elements powered by 2. A magnitude of a vector is represented by the length of a vector and written as |V| for vector V.

        For n-dimensional vector, the magnitude is defined as; |v| = sqrt(v1^2 + v2^2 + ... + vn^2).

        Parameters:
        decimals - the value round up to the given decimal decimals see, Rounding.POINT
        Returns:
        the magnitude of the vector

      • isOrthogonal

        boolean isOrthogonal​(Vector vector)
        If the given vector is orthogonal to the current vector, then it returns true; otherwise it would be false.

        Orthogonality is known as a vector that is perpendicular to the given matrixOld, i.e. if the vector makes the 90 degrees angle with the current matrixOld.

        Parameters:
        vector - the vector to check orthogonality
        Returns:
        true if it's orthogonal

      • isParallel

        boolean isParallel​(Vector vector)
        If the given vector is parallel to the current vector then it returns the factor; otherwise it will be -1.

        The parallel vectors have the same direction but different magnitudes, which means the given vector is scaled up or down in the same or opposite direction of the current vector.

        If a vector V1 = (v1, v2, ... , vn), and a vector W = (w1, w2, ..., wn); where n belongs to the set of Integers. Then the parallel vectors can be written as; W = a(V); where a is a constant (here "the factor"). i.e (w1, w2, ..., wn) = (av1, av2, ..., avn)

        Parameters:
        vector - the vector to check parallelism
        Returns:
        if it's parallel then returns true

      • inverse

        Vector inverse()
        The method will return the inverse vector. The inverse vector satisfy the following equation: V + inverse(V) = 0 (Zero Vector).
        Returns:
        the inverse vector

      • scale

        Vector scale​(double scalar)
        The method will scale the vector by the given value. Please not, this operation is mutable.
        Parameters:
        scalar - the scalar you want to scale the vector with. if:
        • scalar > 1 -> The scaled vector will be scaled up in the same direction.
        • 0 < scalar < 1 -> The scaled vector is shrunk in the same direction.
        • scalar = 0 -> The scaled vector becomes a zero vector.
        • -1 < scalar < 0 -> The scaled vector is shrunk but in the opposite direction.
        • scalar < -1 -> The scaled vector is scaled up but in the opposite direction.
        Returns:
        the self vector but scaled by the given number.

      • transpose

        Vector transpose​(int dimension)
        The method will transpose vector to another dimension. If the given dimension is less then 2 or the same as the vector's dimension then the method will throw InvalidVectorDimensionException exception.

        If I have a two-dimensional vector V = (x, y) and if I transpose the dimension to the 5th dimension then the resulting vector will be, (x, y, 0, 0, 0); the same as if I have a 4-dimensional vector v = (x, y, z, t) and if I try to transpose the vector to the 2nd dimension then the resulting vector will be (x, y).

        Parameters:
        dimension - the dimension to be transposed to
        Returns:
        the transposed vector
        Throws:
        InvalidVectorDimensionException - when the given dimension is less than 2 or the same as the given vector dimension

      • cross

        Vector cross​(Vector vector)
        The method returns the cross product of two vectors. A cross product of two vectors if a new vector, this new vector is perpendicular to both vectors.

        Please note: if two vectors M and N is given then; M x N != N x M When you switch an order, the resulting vector would be in the opposite direction.

        If given vectors are not in 3 dimensions then, InvalidVectorDimensionException is thrown.

        Parameters:
        vector - the second 3 dimensional vector
        Returns:
        the cross product vector
        Throws:
        InvalidVectorDimensionException - when both vectors are in the third dimension.

      • scalarProjection

        double scalarProjection​(Vector vector)
        The method calculates the scalar project of a given vector onto the current vector.

        Let this vector be V and the given vector be W. The scalar projection is defined as, dot(V, W) / magnitude(V)

        Parameters:
        vector - the projecting vector
        Returns:
        the projected scalar

                        Rounding.POINT decimals)

        Let this vector be V and the given vector be W. The scalar projection is defined as, dot(V, W) / magnitude(V)

        Parameters:
        vector - the projecting vector
        decimals - the rounding decimals, Rounding.POINT
        Returns:
        the projected scalar

      • vectorProjection

        Vector vectorProjection​(Vector vector)
        The method calculates the vector project of a given vector onto the current vector. This will produce another vector.

        Let this vector be V and the given vector be W. The vector projection is defined as, [dot(V, W) / magnitude(V)] x V

        Parameters:
        vector - the projecting vector
        Returns:
        the projected scalar

      • vectorRejection

        Vector vectorRejection​(Vector vector)
        The method will return a rejection vector from the the given vector. The projecting vector can be calculated as; R = V - ScalarProjection(W)
        Parameters:
        vector - the projecting vector
        Returns:
        the rejection vector
